<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Soccer Snobbery
   Could Hurt Business
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<LP>
   The Journal certainly jumped on the soccer-bashing
bandwagon in David Brooks's "World Cup: Hooligans and Mad
Cows" (Leisure &amp; Arts, June 19).
   No, I'm not an English hooligan or a West German partial
to funny hats. Born in the U.S., I began playing soccer at
age 12 and haven't stopped. I still play on an over-30 team.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   I think the Journal, and the American media in general,
misses an important point when it comes to soccer. Just as
golf has evolved as a prized means of doing business in
corporate America, a knowledge and understanding of and
affinity for soccer among American business people could be
critical to our economic well-being in the emerging global
economy.
   If that sounds like balderdash, consider some of the
asinine reasons the media give for soccer's flagging success
in America: low-scoring, no hand-eye coordination required,
hooligans, mad cows. Enough already.
   The whole world plays the game. America is part of the
world, even though some closet jingoists continue to deny the
fact.
   It's time to get off our myopic high horse. We may not
know much about soccer, but then again, ask some Italian,
German or Cameroonian who won last year's Super Bowl.
   Jack Bell
   Patterson, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0124
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0124.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ball to Acquire
   European Line
   Of Peter Kiewit
   ----
   By James P. Miller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   BLL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ball Corp. took a big step in its effort to develop a
"more global" focus, by reaching a definitive agreement to
pay $1.03 billion in cash and stock for the European
operations of Continental Can Co.
   Continental Can is a unit of Peter Kiewit Sons' Inc., an
Omaha mining and construction concern. Under the pact, Kiewit
will receive $625 million in cash, and $400 million in Ball
common and preferred stock -- representing a 29% voting stake
in the Muncie, Ind.-based packaging concern.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ball, which has said previously it wants to widen its
international operations, said yesterday it sees "major
strategic opportunities" in the expansion of its currently
small presence in Europe.
   The European packaging market, "and in particular the
beverage can market," Ball said, "is positioned for
significant growth" because of factors including the
reduction in national trade barriers scheduled for 1992, and
the opening of Eastern Bloc markets.
   Continental Can Europe, the region's third-largest
packaging manufacturer, had sales last year of $1.47 billion;
while the unit is profitable, earnings weren't disclosed.
With about 10,000 employees at 32 manufacturing sites in the
United Kingdom, Belgium, the Netherlands, France and Germany,
the operation concentrates in metal containers for food,
beverages and other general containers. It also has interests
in plastic containers.
   Ball "has paid a high price to enter the European market,"
said Rothschild Inc. analyst Jerry Melin, in a reference to
the sales-to-price ratio Ball has agreed to. "From a
long-term strategic perspective," he said, "it's good they
moved into the European market." But after listening to a
Ball presentation yesterday, Mr. Melin said he thinks the
company is at this point "unclear what it is they bought."
   Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben analyst Timothy Burns told Dow
Jones Professional Report, however, that the European
operations are a "crown jewel" whose planned acquisition
represents "outstanding" news.
   Kiewit acquired what was then known as Continental Group
Inc. in 1984, for $2.9 billion, then sold off a number of
non-container operations to pay down the debt. In two
separate transactions, it sold U.S. and Canadian operations
to Crown Cork &amp; Seal Co. for a total $636 million.
   Ball is perhaps best known for the glass preserving-jars
it began manufacturing more than a century ago, but such
products, at 3% of sales, are now overshadowed by its metal
beverage-can operation, which last year provided 58% of
sales. Ball's remaining operations are in diverse aerospace
and industrial markets.
   In 1989, pinched by a competitive can market, the company
reported net income of $35.8 million, or $1.44 a share, on
sales of $1.22 billion. Analysts expect those earnings to
strengthen in the current year as can prices improve.
   Ball said that, in addition to the cash, it will issue
$200 million of common stock, $129 million of voting
convertible exchangeable preferred, and $71 million of a
nonvoting form of the preferred. The company decided to
finance the purchase "with a significant amount of equity so
that we wouldn't be financially constrained from pursuing the
growth prospects of the business, which appear to be
excellent," said Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Richard
M. Ringoen.
   The company said it anticipates a "fairly rapid reduction"
in the financial leverage the deal will create.
   The planned acquisition is subject to approval by Ball
shareholders, as well as clearance by certain U.S. and
foreign regulators.
   Ball also announced yesterday that it will pay $65 million
to buy the remaining 50% interest in its Ball-InCon joint
venture from partner Holland American Investment Corp. The
company said it expects the profitable operation, which had
sales of $536 million last year, to "provide good cash flow."
   Under accounting rules, the venture's sales haven't
previously appeared in the company's totals, and Ball's sales
will now be swollen by the addition in future years of the
operation's sales. Ball said it expects both transactions to
close by year's end.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday,
shares of thinly traded Ball inched up 25 cents, to close at
$32.75.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0123
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0123.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Possible Solution
   To S&amp;L Quagmire
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   I have a possible solution to the S&amp;L mess (page one, July
3).
   Have two types of deposits: uninsured and insured. The
uninsured deposits will pay market interest rates to the
depositor, the insured ones two points below. The two points
will go to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., to cover the
insurance. Thus, the cost to the financial institution will
be the same. The depositor will watch the performance of his
bank and decide how safe its operation is. We eliminate giant
federal supervision. The financial institution should publish
figures monthly so everybody can figure out the depositors'
confidence in the financial institution and its performance.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Some private evaluators will appear to advise depositors,
the funds generally will stay close to home, the amount of
large, brokered deposits will decrease, and the two points
going to the FDIC may be used to pay for the current bailout.
   Michael Hoch
   Professor Emeritus of Materials Science
   University of Cincinnati
   Cincinnati
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0122
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0122.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Beverly Enterprises
   To Offer Debentures
   Totaling $40 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   BEV
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   PASADENA, Calif. -- Beverly Enterprises Inc. said it plans
a public offering of $40 million of convertible debentures,
which would be the second major sale of securities this year
by the health-care concern.
   Beverly, which is moving its headquarters to Fort Smith,
Ark., effective tomorrow, said proceeds from the new issue
will be used in its continuing financial restructuring. The
offering will be managed by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Beverly shares closed at $6.375, down 25 cents.
   A Beverly spokesman said the debentures will be
convertible at the greater of either $8 face amount of
debenture for each new common share, or a 20% premium over
market value at the time the sale is completed. At the
$8-a-share rate, the issue is convertible into a total of
five million new common shares. The company has about 65
million common shares outstanding.
   Beverly, which operates nursing facilities,
retirement-living centers and home-health centers, sold 11.5
million new common shares last March through a public
offering that netted the company about $45.7 million.
Proceeds from that issue, as with the plan for the latest
offering, were used to refinance debt.
   Schuyler Hollingsworth, Beverly vice president and
treasurer, said the company has about $470 million in debt to
be restructured. Following completion of the planned
debenture sale, Beverly plans three further transactions
later this year, including bank borrowings and private
placements, to complete the debt refinancing, Mr.
Hollingsworth said.
</TEXT>
