<HL>
   Wang Reports
   Widened Loss
   For 4th Period
   ---
   Charges and Write-Downs
   Totaled $496.7 Million;
   Revenue Declined 13%
   ----
   By William M. Bulkeley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   WANB
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Wang Laboratories Inc. took $417.4 million in one-time
write-downs and restructuring charges, resulting in a widened
net loss of $496.7 million, or $3.01 a share, for the fourth
quarter ended June 30.
   The Lowell, Mass.-based maker of minicomputers and office
automation equipment said revenue continued to decline,
dropping 13% to $652.2 million from $750.9 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Despite the loss, Richard W. Miller, chairman and chief
executive officer, was upbeat. He said that without the
one-time charges Wang would have had a loss on continuing
operations of $5.6 million, which he characterized as "near
break-even." He added, "We achieved our fourth-quarter goal
of bringing our operating revenues and operating expenses
into balance."
   Mr. Miller, who was brought in as president last summer in
the midst of a financial crisis, predicted that in fiscal
1991, Wang will achieve its first profitable year since
fiscal 1988. He said he doesn't expect any further
write-downs or restructuring charges.
   Stock analysts, while praising Wang's cost-cutting moves,
remained skeptical about Wang's future. "The underlying issue
remains whether and when they can get revenue to expand
rather than contract," said Marc Schulman, an analyst with
UBS Securities Inc.
   In American Stock Exchange composite trading, Wang Class B
stock rose 25 cents to $4.125.
   In the year-earlier fourth quarter, Wang had a net loss of
$374.7 million, or $2.29 a share. That loss included one-time
charges of $234 million and an operating loss of $61.1
million.
   Mr. Miller said Wang took the latest round of write-offs
to cover declines in value "in the whole infrastructure
rather than having this plague us as we go forward."
   Some of the write-offs involve inventories of unneeded
parts, inventories of older Wang computers, service depot
inventories that aren't needed because new computers are more
reliable then older ones and sales and service facilities
that have been consolidated or have declined in value. He
said Wang has closed an operation that previously rebuilt and
resold Wang computers that were traded in by customers.
   Mr. Miller said in the current quarter Wang will reduce
its staff by more than 1,000 people to about 19,500. Wang
currently has 20,900 employees, down 27% from a year earlier.
In Lowell, it has cut employment 34% to 6,085 from 9,174 a
year ago.
   Mr. Miller said that after the write-downs "we've done
everything we wanted to do. Revenue and expense are in line."
He noted that Wang has paid off all but $30 million of the
$575 million in bank debt that caused the cash crisis last
year. Despite the charges, Wang has $165 million in cash and
is generating cash from operations, he said.
   Mr. Miller declined to predict results for the current
quarter. Jay P. Stevens, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc., said "the tone for the whole industry is to be careful
about (predicting) the summer quarter." He said he thinks
Wang may earn 25 cents a share for the full fiscal year.
   For fiscal 1990, Wang reported a net loss of $715.9
million, or $4.35 a share, compared with a net loss of $424.3
million, or $2.59 a share. The latest year includes
restructuring and other special charges of $388.3 million and
losses from discontinued operations of $87.3 million. The
year-earlier period included restructuring and special
charges of $142 million and losses from discontinued
operations of $100.1 million.
   Revenue for the year fell 14% to $2.5 billion from $2.91
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0115
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0115.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Bookshorts: Our Contributors on Poetry and Management
   ----
   By Raymond Sokolov
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<LP>
   Willard Spiegelman, perhaps best known in these quarters
as the Leisure &amp; Arts page's man in Dallas, spends his days
professing English at Southern Methodist University, editing
the Southern Review and writing about poetry, notably
Wordsworth. Lately, however, he has been turning his mind to
poets of his own time. The result is "The Didactic Muse:
Scenes of Instruction in Contemporary American Poetry"
(Princeton, 278 pages, $39.50 cloth, $10.95 paper).
   While Mr. Spiegelman brings a scholar's precision to this
work, he has obviously been at pains to open up the subject
for outsiders, as it were, by showing how the eight writers
he has chosen all have set themselves up as teachers in their
poems. This is something of a radical notion, joining such
apparently unrelated temperaments as the Beat standard bearer
Allen Ginsberg and the patrician James Merrill to a chain of
pedagogic forebears stretching back to the Vergil of the
"Georgics."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The more immediate mentor of this lyrically educative gang
is W.H. Auden, whose "easy speech," Mr. Spiegelman says,
sounds like meditation "at random" but actually propounds
serious lessons about the state of the world. From Auden, the
analysis proceeds from poet to poet, construing their very
different work as a rhetoric of instruction and
argumentation. If this sounds arid in summary, in the doing
it becomes a didactic revelation, a literal introduction or
leading-in to some great writers, the best of them often
misunderstood.
   Adrienne Rich benefits most from this approach. Although
few readers of this feminist poet will be surprised to see
her treated as a didactic, many will be amazed to see how
what may have looked like artless preaching actually gets its
power from an eminently calculated and interesting rhetoric.
As Mr. Spiegelman shows, one of Ms. Rich's characteristic
methods is to make a point with lists (a feature of didactic
poetry as old as Homer's catalog of Greek ships). A woman in
the poem "Transcendental Etude" goes off by herself to the
kitchen and fusses quietly with "bits of yarn, calico and
velvet scraps,/laying them out absently on the scrubbed
boards/in the lamplight, with small rainbow-colored
shells/sent in cotton-wool from somewhere far away/and skeins
of milkweed from the nearest meadow . . ."
   Such poetry -- really all serious poetry -- has only a
handful of readers today, perhaps because in a previous
generation, T.S. Eliot and the other high modernists cut
themselves off from the large public poetry had always had
before. The more recent landscape of verse is not nearly such
a dark wood, but its paths need mapping. Mr. Spiegelman has
been working at this task in a timely way, then, and a direct
benefit could accrue from his efforts to Anthony Hecht, whose
complete works have just been republished as "Collected
Earlier Poems" (Knopf, 288 pages, $22.95), along with a new
volume, "The Transparent Man" (Knopf, 96 pages, $18.95). Mr.
Spiegelman also makes it his central task to clarify the
importance of Mr. Merrill's encyclopedic long poem, "The
Changing Light at Sandover," declaring that it "has
permanently altered the course of American poetry for the
rest of our century."
   ---
   No one needs to be persuaded that management is important
or taught that business's ignore it at their peril. The
difficulty, in a way oddly parallel to the problem of talking
cogently about poetry, is to find a rhetoric, a way into
writing about the subject that will not strike the
intelligent reader as empty, jejune, bombastic or all three
at once. David Asman's job, as editor of this newspaper's
"Manager's Journal" column since 1983, has been to solve this
problem. Now he has edited "The Wall Street Journal on
Managing: Adding Value Through Synergy" (Doubleday Currency,
256 pages, $19.95). All of the essays originally appeared in
the "Manager's Journal," but they have been re-edited for
this book and brought up-to-date, to take into account late
developments in the economy and a rapidly changing
geopolitical setting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0114
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0114.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Bush, Congressional Leaders to Meet
   Again on Scheduling of Budget Talks
   ----
   By David Wessel and Michel McQueen
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
BEVERAGES (BVG)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Still maneuvering over schedules rather than
substance, President Bush and top congressional leaders are
to meet again this morning to attempt to fashion a timetable
for the deficit-reduction talks, the White House said.
   As Republican budget negotiators left a meeting with Mr.
Bush yesterday, they complained that their Democratic
counterparts were dragging their feet. "We've walked the
extra mile on revenues," said Senate Republican Leader Robert
Dole of Kansas. "We've laid out a specific plan and we're
still waiting to hear from the Democrats."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bill Frenzel (R., Minn) said he and some other
Republican budget negotiators urged Mr. Bush to demand that
Congress delay the start of its scheduled recess. But other
GOP congressional leaders -- and some administration
officials, as well -- counseled a less confrontational
approach and are resigned to waiting until the fall to get
down to hard bargaining. White House Chief of Staff John
Sununu is already meeting with Republican strategists to
develop a consistent public explanation for the plodding
progress of the talks.
   Democrats, though not refusing to put forward a plan,
continue to question the wisdom of doing so before Congress
begins its August recess. "It is not particularly useful to
have plans publicly aired, and then not the subject of
negotiations in an active, continuous basis for days or a
couple of weeks," Speaker Thomas Foley (D., Wash.) said.
   Democrats are divided internally on both tactics and
substance, but privately say they are prepared to agree to
present a proposal on a specific date in late August or early
September. If Republicans threaten to delay the congressional
recess, then Democratic staff members expect Democratic
leaders to endorse a plan -- crafted largely as a political
statement of the party's priorities -- that relies on deep
cuts in defense and on tax increases aimed at the rich.
   As previously reported, the draft Republican
deficit-reduction plan for fiscal 1991, which starts Oct. 1,
would raise taxes on beer, wine and liquor; cap the deduction
for state and local income taxes at $10,000; cut capital
gains tax rates; trim spending on defense by $7 billion and
trim spending on government benefit programs -- but not
Social Security -- by about $16 billion.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Daniel Moynihan is preparing to unveil a
revision of his proposal to reduce Social Security payroll
taxes. He wants to make it more attractive to his
deficit-fearing colleagues when he offers it as an amendment
to a must-pass bill to raise the federal debt ceiling this
week or next.
   Instead of slashing the payroll tax over two years, aides
say the New York Democrat today will propose phasing in the
tax cut by dropping the Social Security tax by 0.2 percentage
point a year for five years beginning in fiscal 1991. Workers
currently pay 6.2% of their earnings under $51,300 for Social
Security; employers match that.
   The new plan would cost the Treasury $6.6 billion in
fiscal 1991 and $147.6 billion over five years, Sen. Moynihan
figures. His original proposal to cut the tax rate to 6.06%
in the current year and 5.1% in 1991 would have cost the
Treasury $4.4 billion this fiscal year and $38 billion in
fiscal 1991. Sen. Moynihan wouldn't alter the additional
1.45% payroll tax that goes to finance Medicare.
   The House is scheduled today to consider raising the debt
ceiling to $3.444 trillion from $3.122 trillion, sufficient
to allow government borrowing through September 1991. Mr.
Foley warned that the measure may fail the first time, but he
has said that the House won't begin its recess until it lifts
the debt ceiling.
   The House Ways and Means Committee has approved an
alternative, which isn't slated for consideration today, that
would authorize the Treasury to keep borrowing only through
Oct. 15.
   The Treasury says it will default unless Congress lifts
the debt ceiling by Aug. 15.
   The congressional recess is scheduled to begin Friday,
although Senate leaders say they may delay their departure.
Mr. Bush is currently scheduled to begin a vacation in Maine
on Aug. 10.
   ---
   Carl Johnston contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
