<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   The Jesse and Pat Bill
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   To your average Congressperson, a vote to choke off shoe,
textile and clothing imports seems like a nice opportunity to
make everybody happy. Members can stand up to crafty
foreigners and collect brownie points -- and maybe a little
PAC money -- from trade unions and the textile lobby. Then
the President will veto the bill and the world trading system
can chug on unharmed.
   That's what happened with the 1985 and 1988 textile bills.
But the 1990 bill, which passed the Senate last week and
probably will come before the House this week, is not just
innocent grandstanding. The real aim of its backers is to
wreck the current Uruguay round of free-trade talks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Important Republicans -- Senate leader Bob Dole for one --
are joining the protectionist camp. And other Senators,
ranging from Jesse Helms to Pat Moynihan, are quite willing
to forsake their usual principles to add their votes and
voices.
   Even without the 1990 textile bill, the textile industry
is by far the most protected in the country. Under the terms
of the Multifiber Agreement, the U.S. has signed 38 bilateral
"agreements" imposing quotas on the textile and clothing
exports of Japan and 37 other countries. (European countries
and the U.S. refrain from imposing such restrictions on each
other under what trade lawyers call "the white man's rule.")
   Those imports that the U.S. does accept are then smacked
with tariffs of nearly 20%, four times the average U.S. rate.
The Federal Trade Commission calculates that the restrictions
cost the American consumer an extra 58% on every towel,
shirt, dress and pair of underwear, which adds up to a total
yearly bill between $7.5 billion and $11.5 billion (in 1984
dollars).
   That's not enough for the textile lobby. The bill the
Senate enacted last week rips up those 38 quota agreements
and imposes a single import quota on the whole world -- a
quota that is permitted to grow by no more than 1% per year.
In effect, the U.S. textile and clothing industries are
guaranteed their present market share of about 65% forever.
   Whatever the average Senator thought he was doing, the
principal backers of this legislation were signaling the
administration: Don't bother bringing home a treaty from
Uruguay if it includes free trade in textiles. And they were
signaling the rest of the world: Don't bother making
concessions to U.S. trade negotiators on intellectual
property, high technology and agriculture in exchange for
U.S. concessions on textiles, because the administration's
promises won't be honored by the Senate.
   President Bush, who bravely defended free trade in the
1988 primary in textile-producing South Carolina, is almost
certain to veto the bill, and his veto probably will be
sustained. But the message would be sent nonetheless. Both
the administration and foreigners will notice that the number
of free-trade Senators is steadily eroding: 39 voted against
the 1985 textile bill, 36 against the 1988 bill and just 32
against this year's version.
   This is a shameful situation, and no two Senators should
be more ashamed of it, or their part in it, than the
arch-conservative Mr. Helms and the arch-liberal Mr.
Moynihan. Plenty of other Senators agree that Americans
should be forced to pay half again as much for their socks as
they need to, but no two other Senators have had to stray
quite so far from their principles.
   It's certainly strange to see Mr. Helms -- who opposes
quotas so fiercely when they are enacted in, say, a
civil-rights bill -- lobby for them so passionately in a
trade bill. In other contexts, Mr. Helms is one of the
Senate's staunchest advocates of competition and
self-reliance. Yet for the textile industry of North Carolina
he demands that competitors be excluded from the market and
that the 30 years of special government favors to the
industry be continued indefinitely.
   It's even stranger to see Mr. Moynihan, supposedly a
friend of the poor, voting for more textile protectionism,
which hits the poor hardest. He's even more outspoken about
his commitment to the international rule of law, but his vote
for the textile bill was a vote to tear up 38 U.S. government
foreign agreements without so much as an "excuse me." Mr.
Moynihan finds an affront to international law in unilateral
American action to liberate small Caribbean countries; but
unilateral American action to devastate the economies of
countries like Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and Thailand apparently
is perfectly OK.
   Uruguay offers the hope that international trade can move
toward greater competitiveness and legality. That's an
aspiration that both Sen. Moynihan and Sen. Helms, who claim
to be politicians of conviction, say they support. They --
and their colleagues -- should cease sabotaging it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0089
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0089.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   House Panel
   To Propose New
   Weapons Rules
   ----
   By Andy Pasztor
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   NOC
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Armed Services Committee is
expected to propose ground rules today aimed at continuing
development but delaying production of several major weapons,
including the next generation of Air Force fighters and Army
helicopters.
   The committee, in a major departure from traditional
weapons-buying plans, is leaning strongly toward shelving
production of the so-called Advanced Tactical Fighter and LH
attack helicopter until prototype aircraft are thoroughly
tested, according to lawmakers and congressional staff
members. The programs carry a combined price tag of nearly
$85 billion, and they are inviting targets for deep cuts
because neither has begun production.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Meanwhile, proponents of the B-2 Stealth bomber, built by
Los Angeles-based Northrop Corp., have given up the struggle
to try to buy two more of the embattled planes next year.
Instead of fighting for the nearly $2.5 billion of B-2
production funds requested by the Bush administration, House
supporters are now resigned to trying to retain a symbolic
$200 million in long-lead production money to avoid layoffs
and keep subcontractors in place.
   But Rep. Ike Skelton (D., Mo.), one of the radar-evading
plane's leading supporters, yesterday failed to convince a
subcommittee to authorize the $200 million during a
closed-door session. His amendment, Rep. Skelton said, "means
{the B-2} would, at least, stay alive." But it isn't clear
whether he and his supporters will push for a vote in the
committee, which is strongly opposed to buying more planes.
Supporters of the B-2, however, are betting that the Senate
will salvage the bomber.
   Blaming much of the B-2's political troubles on months of
lukewarm White House support, Rep. Skelton acknowledged that
the House is almost certain to eliminate all 1991 production
funds for the bomber. The Senate version of the bill,
however, contains nearly $2 billion for B-2 production. And
both measures include money to complete research and testing.
   Under the broad new procurement guidelines, spearheaded by
Chairman Les Aspin (D., Wis.), the Pentagon would have to
demonstrate the effectiveness of sophisticated avionics,
engines, computers and related equipment before committing to
even low-rate production of proposed aircraft. The goal is to
help the military and industry avoid making multibillion
dollar investments in tooling and other expensive overhead
before weapons have undergone rigorous testing. The B-2 isn't
expected to be affected by the proposal, lawmakers and
committee aides said.
   A number of former high-ranking Pentagon acquisition
officials have testified that such changes are necessary in
light of shrinking military budgets, and Rep. Aspin and his
aides have mulled over the idea since at least January. But
as late as yesterday, lawmakers were working out some of the
details.
   Many industry and Pentagon officials, however, are opposed
to the concept of developing weapons but then stopping short
of full-scale production, while research begins on a
more-advanced version of the same weapon. Air Force Secretary
Donald Rice, for instance, has said that putting
technological advances on the shelf rather than in the field
will provide arms makers in the Soviet Union and other
nations an opportunity to catch up to the U.S.
   Some lawmakers and committee aides said the new ground
rules, if they are part of the final defense spending bill
for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, also will slow down
procurement of the Navy's fast, super-quiet Seawolf attack
submarines.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee earlier this month
voted to withhold production or full-scale development
funding for the Seawolf, LH helicopters, the Air Force's ATF
and the Navy's proposed A-12 carrier-based attack plane. But
the House panel, according to lawmakers and aides, is
expected to propose specific criteria for production
decisions.
   Rep. William Dickinson (R., Ala.), the committee's ranking
GOP member and a major supporter of Army aviation, said in an
interview last week that he was ready to accept significant
delays and cutbacks in the LH's planned production schedule.
"I wouldn't fall on my sword" over cuts, he said, adding, "I
think we've got a fight on our hands" simply to keep the
program alive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0088
</DOCNO>
