<HL>
   Credit Ratings:
   Some Massachusetts Debt
   Stays on S&amp;P CreditWatch
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. kept Massachusetts'
triple-B rated general obligation bonds on its CreditWatch
list with negative implications.
   The ratings agency said the watch reflects the state's
continued failure to pass a new budget and the continuing
uncertainty over whether a sales tax on services that was
passed will be reconsidered by the legislature.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It also said there are concerns about a tax-cutting
initiative that voters will consider in November.
   Standard &amp; Poor's said that "legislative inaction over the
last two years" has left $1.8 billion in operating deficits
over the last two years and promise "a legacy of debt for
perhaps the next two administrations." It said "while the
economy is in a recession, long-term prospects remain
positive."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900731-0045
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900731-0045.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- LTV Corp.:
   Concern Reports Earnings
   Rose Sharply in 2nd Period
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   LTV
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
EARNINGS (ERN)
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   LTV Corp., Dallas, said second-quarter net income more
than doubled because of a special gain this year and a
special charge a year earlier.
   Net rose to $76.6 million, or 59 cents a share, from $30.3
million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier. The 1990
quarter reflected a gain of $44.3 million on the sale of a
stainless steel unit. The 1989 quarter was reduced by $80
million in write-downs and charges on aircraft production
assets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Operating profit fell 64% to $36.6 million from $102.6
million before charges a year earlier. Revenue fell 4.5% to
$1.59 billion from $1.66 billion.
   Steel operations contributed almost all of the decline in
operating profit. LTV, which is operating under protection of
bankruptcy law, attributed the decline to lower prices, lower
sales and higher labor costs.
   In the first half, profit rose to $120.8 million, or 91
cents a share, from $106.9 million, or 82 cents a share, a
year earlier. Revenue fell 6% to $3.08 billion from $3.28
billion.
</TEXT>
