   International Brief -- Banco Espanol de Credito:
   Spanish Bank's Pretax Profit
   For First Half Surged 17%
</HL>
<DATE>
07/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   E.BCE
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Banco Espanol de Credito of Spain reported that first-half
pretax profit surged 17% to 35.29 billion pesetas ($357.2
million).
   The bank, known as Banesto, said financial revenue grew
33% to 212.29 billion pesetas, boosted by a 41% jump in loans
and financial instruments. It didn't provide comparative
data.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Banesto's efforts to lure depositors, by offering
high-yield "super accounts" with interest rates of about 13%,
helped increase consumer deposits and bolster financial
revenue, but the accounts also sharply raised financial
costs, which soared 50% to 142.87 billion pesetas, the bank
said.
   Analysts said the results were better than expected, and
noted that Spain's big banks have been able to offset the
burden of high-yield accounts by increasing loan rates and
service charges.
